<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>The RCP welcomes the opportunity to submit written evidence to the House of Commons Health Select Committee inquiry on Public expenditure on health and social care</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Royal College of Physicians </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Rcp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (PEX 0023)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Royal College of Physicians (RCP) plays a leading role in the delivery of high quality patient care by setting standards of medical practice and promoting clinical excellence.  We provide physicians in the United Kingdom and overseas with education, training and support throughout their careers.  As an independent body representing almost 29,000 fellows and members worldwide, we advise and work with government, the public, patients and other professions to improve health and healthcare. Our primary interest is in building a health system that delivers high quality care for patients. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The RCP welcomes the opportunity to submit written evidence to the House of Commons Health Select Committee inquiry on Public expenditure on health and social care. We would like to make the following comments. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We believe that the overall funding of the NHS is currently lower than the levels of funding in other, comparable, developed countries.  Recent real term cuts and the effects of the efficiency challenge have contributed to the financial instability of many hospitals, especially smaller ones, and also to examples of poor care in hospital.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We feel that extra funding for health and social care </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could come from either general taxation or via redistribution from other areas.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We understand that the fair geographical distribution of resources is not easy to achieve. However, we feel that calculations based on deprivation ignore, to an extent, the greater effects of age on NHS usage in old age, regardless of affluence.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At present, we believe that many NHS trusts cannot cope with the increasing burden of acute care. Improvements across community and social care are urgently required to assist with this.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Recruiting senior and junior medical staff is seen as a major problem in emergency departments by some.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It seems that general practice is also overwhelmed; extra doctors would help as would an increase of secondary staff working in the community, but both of these solutions would carry a cost.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><div style="width:8.55pt; height:17.05pt; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">2</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64